Question (1 point): Briefly discuss the variable types and distributional implications such as potential skewness and outliers.

The first thing I noticed is that the mean and median values are about the same for all of the variables, which implies a normal distribution. Then, I examined whether the number of data points collected for each of the sexes and classes are equal. For the sexes, the number of observations are about the same. However, the size of the samples for each of the classes vary greatly. This variability makes me question the validity of research. Next, to get a sense of the outliers, I looked at the minimum and maximum values for all of the variables. Using the simple formula IQR x 1.5, I investigated whether the the minimum and maximum values of each of the variables are outliers. For length, diameter, and height, the minimum values are outliers. For whole, shuck, and volume, the maximum values are outliers. For rings, both minimum and maximum values are outliers. Outliers can cause skewness and kurtosis, which makes them a point of concern.

Essay Question (5 points) How well do you think these variables would perform as predictors of age? Explain.

Volume, whole weight, and rings appear as though they would perform well as predictors of age since the boxplot location for each class is fairly distinct. For both Volume vs Class and Whole weight vs Class, the graphs demonstrate that the older the abalone, the greater the volume and weight. The center of the distributions, the boxplots, are higher on both graphs as the class gets older. However, this distinction is better for Classes A1, A2, and A3. For A4 and A5, the distributions for Volume and Whole Weight are too similar, and it would be difficult to differentiate between the two classes. Another concern is that the whiskers for A3, A4, and A5 all extend far. These very wide distributions make it difficult to use Volume and Whole Weight as predictors of age. For example, given a volume of 700 cm^3, it would be hard to predict whether it belongs to A3, A4, or A5. When it comes to Volume and Whole Weight vs Rings, the number of rings increase with the age, yet the volume and whole weight distributions are not distinct. Therefore, these would not be useful as predictors of age. For example, classes A3, A4, and A5, all have wide distributions unlike for A1 which is clustered at the lower portion of the graphs for both Volume and Whole Weight. Overall, these graphs indicate that as the abalones get older, it gets increasingly difficult to use these physical measurements to predict age.

### Section 6: (11 points) Conclusions from the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA).

Conclusions

Essay Question 1) (5 points) Based solely on these data, what are plausible statistical reasons that explain the failure of the original study? Consider to what extent physical measurements may be used for age prediction.

First, the number of samples for each class vary greatly. The reseachers should have collected an similar amount of observations for each class. Unequal sample sizes would make it difficult to compare the data between classes because of the power of outliers. An outlier for a smaller sample would make a big impact compared to an outlier for a larger sample. The graphs I produced did show the presence of outliers which makes it difficult to use the physical measurements as predictors of age. For example, for the Volume and Whole Weight, the classes A3, A4, and A5 have long whiskers which makes the distinctions between distributions questionable. Lastly, there is a question of why female abalones have a higher overall volume and shuck when compared to males. This gender difference makes it difficult to use physical measurements to predict age since for example, a higher volume could indicate older age or a different gender.

Essay Question 2) (3 points) Do not refer to the abalone data or study. If you were presented with an overall histogram and summary statistics from a sample of some population or phenomenon and no other information, what questions might you ask before accepting them as representative of the sampled population or phenomenon?

Data collection is the first step so my primary concern is to learn how the data was gathered, especially if the data is from an observational study. I would need to know the size of the sample. A large enough sample size is necessary to represent a population. The size of the sample would depend on the size of the population. Another cause of concern is the location from which the data was gathered. Does the sample come from a location or locations that represent the location of the population? Are there enough observations from each location if there are several? If my population is fish from the ocean, gathering information about fish from a lake would not suffice. Next, the characteristics of the sample must reflect the population. For example, if the population focuses on a certain age group, the sample should come from that specific age group. As for the histogram, I would look at the x-axis and y-axis to evaluate whether they appropriately represent the data without bias. The number of bins is crucial and would also need to be evaluated. I would look at the distribution, examine its normalcy, and be on the lookout for outliers. In summary, I would make sure that the data collection is appropriate, the sample is representative, and the histogram accurately represents the data.

Essay Question 3) (3 points) Do not refer to the abalone data or study. What do you see as difficulties analyzing data derived from observational studies? Can causality be determined? What might be learned from such studies?

Observational studies are great for determining correlation between variables. However, correlation does not mean causation. Causality can never be determined based simply on an observational study due to the likelihood of confounding variables. Concluding that one variable directly causes another just based on the strength of their relationship should be avoided. A controlled study would be more appropriate for determining causality, although there is still risk of false claims even from tightly controlled studies. Observational studies can only provide trends and insights which can help to analyze the relationships between variables, but causality cannot be determined.
